<section xml:id="State_Hodge">
  <title>The Hodge theorem</title>
  <p>
    Unfortunately,
    it is far from trivial that the variational problem<nbsp/><xref ref="x2-1"/> can be solved.
    The PDE theory,
    especially the elliptic regularity theory kicks in here to make the above arguments rigid.
  </p>
  <theorem>
    <title>real Hodge Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>M</m> be a compact orientable Riemannian manifold.
        Let <m>p\geq 0</m>.
        Define
        <me>
          \mathcal H^p(M)=\{\phi\in\Lambda^p(M))\mid \Delta\phi=0\}
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\dim \mathcal H^p(M)\lt +\infty</m>;
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Let <m>\eta</m> be an arbitrary smooth <m>p</m>-form.
              Then we have
              <me>
                \eta=\eta_0+d\eta_1+\delta\eta_2
              </me>,
              where <m>\eta_0</m> is a harmonic <m>p</m>-form;
              <m>\eta_1</m> and <m>\eta_2</m> are <m>(p-1)</m> and <m>(p+1)</m> forms,
              respectively,
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>H^p_{DR}(M)=\mathcal H^p(M)</m> for <m>p\geq 0</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
</section>